Notes: Members of 33 villages in the Sabce commune protested in favor of returning a recently expelled prefect to his position in the municipality.
Workers marched in protest of high costs of living.
University students marched in favor of changing the License-Master-Doctorate system.
Protesters marched in favor of the new electoral code which excludes supporters of former president Campaore.
Thousands protested in favor of the new electoral code that excludes supporters of former president Campaore.
Workers from the African Pneumatic Society joined by the UAS union marched to demand payment of housing allowances.
An ongoing dispute between farmers and herders in a village near Ziniare led to riots where property was burned and some livestock killed. Police intervened with teargas and arrested three.

Unions and civil society organizations launched a general strike to protest high costs of living and around 5,000 people held a protest. Most businesses remained open, with only the University of Ouagadougou following the strike for the entire day.
Thousands marched in protest of high cost of living.
Protesters marched against high costs of living.
Protesters marched against high costs of living.

While a vote took place to block members of the former regime from upcoming elections, protesters both for and against the amendment chanted in the streets and one group blocked a road and burned tires. Small clashes broke out with the police who used teargas and arrested five.
Protesters marched against political discrimination in light of an upcoming vote to exclude members of the former regime from the next elections.
About 30 protesters marched against a law that would exclude members of the former regime from upcoming elections. They were dispersed by police using tear gas.

5 gunmen attacked a security vehicle near a mine, shooting and injuring the driver and a policeman and kidnapping a Romanian security officer who was unarmed. They then headed towards Mali or Niger. One month later, Al-Mourabitoun confirmed that they still had the Romanian in their custody.
Hundreds of truck drivers marched to demand better work and living conditions, including increased wages.
Truck drivers went on a 48 hour strike to improve working conditions. They blocked the route from Ouagadougou to Bobo-Dioulasso.
Workers from the Regional Direction of Labor and Social Security held a sit-in to express discontent with an incident with gendarmes they day before.
Brakina and Sodibo brewery workers went on strike, stopping all work at the factories in Ouagadougou and Bobo Dioulassoand, holding a sit-in to demand higher wages.
Brakina and Sodibo brewery workers went on strike, stopping all work at the factories in Ouagadougou and Bobo Dioulassoand, holding a sit-in to demand higher wages.
New Patriotic Party (NPP) members and supporters marched in Kumasi in protest over economic hardships, power cuts, and the long period of piloting the National Health Insurance Scheme in the region

Ghanaians, Cameroonians and Burkinabe came together to presented a petition to ask the Nigerian president to treat the abduction of schoolgirls by Boko Haram as an international incident and do more to solve it

Members of the Ghana National Petroleum Tanker Drivers Union (GNPTDU) refused to allow any vehicle to load petrol from the Accra BOST depot in protest of BOSTs alleged destruction of their office, and to demand it be rebuilt
Hundreds of women marched in Accra to the Nigerian embassy to present a petition protesting the kidnapping of girls in Nigeria by Boko Haram

A photographer was assualted by a military officer after he tried to take pictures of a confrontation between military personnel and some youths of the area. His camera was destroyed and some of his equipment was seized.
Ghanaians workers protested in Black Star Square in Accra to demand improvements to working conditions and better pay
Residents of Matuu town, Machakos county, took to the streets to protest demolition of kiosks by the county government.
Elegeyo-Marakwet residents protest over a road overgrown with foliage, causing passage difficult.
Hundreds of women staged a demonstration to protest against their husbands neglect of family responsibilities.
Protesters against insecurity throw stones at a bus and raid a Somali-owned hotel in Mwingi. Police shot into the air to disperse the mob.

An unknown assailant threw two grenades into a cafe in Garissa on Wednesday night, wounding two people. The source references several attacks from al Shabaab in the area, but does not speculate as to who is responsible for the Wednesday blast.
Al Shabaab lines and executes 15 non-Muslim farmers by firing squad in Mado Gashi.
At least one patron is killed when suspected al Shabaab attack a country club bar in Wajir. Witnesses claim two blasts followed by gunfire.

A pro-al Shabaab website published a report that al Shabaab has claimed the responsibility of the killing of 36-non local Kenyans at a quarry in Koromei area near Mandera in the night of 01/12. The statement claimed that the attack on Koromei was part of series of attacks executed by the Mujahidin to serve as a response to Kenyas occupation of Somalia, the airstrikes by Kenyan warplanes and the killing of innocent Somalis.
A group protesting area insecurity become entangled in running battles with police. Twelve students were treated for injuries at area hospitals.
At least five people were wounded on Sunday evening after unknown men hurled a hand grenade at pedestrians in Garissa town, northern Kenya.
A Kenyan police officer was shot dead and another seriously wounded in an attack by suspected al Shabaab at Dadaab Refugee Camp.
Nyandarua residents protested against delay in constructing the 45km Mairo-Inya Shamata road. The residents barricaded the road for most of the day.
University of Nairobi students protest a policy that would not pay interns.
A group continues a protest against insecurity in Nairobis CBD.

Civil society groups took to the streets, torching coffins to protest against recent Mandera violence and rising insecurity in the region. Police dispersed the crowd when they neared the Office of the President, Harambee House.
Residents of Embu Town on Friday night lynched a suspected mugger who had accosted a man and robbed him of his cash.

At least 28 people were killed after suspected Al-Shabaab militants attacked a Nairobi-bound bus in Omar Jilo, Mandera County in north-east Kenya. Witness said the attackers ordered all off the bus, divided the passengers along ethnic lines - Somali and non-Somali, shooting all non-Somalis. Many of the deceased were teachers.
A group of internally displaced people in Gilgil protested at the office of the deputy county commissioner demanding to be given relief food.
At least five people were killed and four others reported missing following clashes in Dukana, Marsabit County or rights to cattle and property.
A group protests attacks on women based on wearing revealing attire.
A mob of men attacked and stripped a woman after accusing her of being inappropriately dressed. The assault comes hours after a group protested such attacks.
Molasses traders protest a buyer over perceived favouritism given to conglomerates.

Four are killed in Kisauni by ""radical youth"" on the evening of 17/11. Police suspect that the incident may have been a revenge attack for the killing of a youth at Masgid Shuhadaa during a raid on two Mosques in Kisauni the previous evening.

University of Nairobi students riot over a prolonged power blackout. The students stoned motorists driving by and robbed pedestrians who were using the road at the time of the blackout. No injuries reported.
Hundreds of residents invaded a 60,000-acre ranch in Taita Taveta belonging to a cooperative in protest of land grabbing by a third party.
Police raid two Kisauni mosques during the evening hours, arrest 250+ suspects. One death from the raids reported.
A womens group in suburban Nairobi protests lenient penalties on the sale of illegal alcohol.
Two suspected criminals were beaten up and burned by a mob in Chuka Igambangombe constituency. Police rescued the suspects, who suffered severe burns.

At least eight people were killed and four others seriously injured in inter- communal clashes in northern Kenyas Isiolo County. The clash reportedly lasted for several hours. The clash occurred at Leruko on Isiolo side, a few meters from the bridge that connects Isiolos Buffalo Springs game reserve with Samburu Park.

One is dead and several injured when a group protesting over extra-judicial killings and insecurity becomes violent. Several roads were also reported barricaded. The riot was centrally sparked to avenge the killing of terror suspect Hassan Guti. Several arrests reported.
A tribal clash over land causes the death of one and several houses destroyed. The clash occurred in Kuvasali village, Kakamega County.

Unidentified persons shoot and kill an al Shabaab suspect in the Majengo area. The suspect was driving with his wife and niece. The assailants are rumoured to be members of a Kenyan Anti-militant unit. The killing sparked a violent protest several days later.
Residents protest in Lodwar over area insecurity for a second day.

A Kapseret MP is slapped, pushed to the ground and stamped on the chest for refusing to comply with a police traffic order. The action spurred a protest against the police. Exact date not known - source date is 07/11.

Students protest in Lodwar, Turkana county over recent insecurity in the region. The group threatened to halt oil exploration in the area if the government did not act. The protest is mainly a reaction to an attack on a police post in Kapedo over the weekend.

A security operation against a group of Pokot militia yields the recovery of weapons and the deaths of six bandits, who had been launching attacks in the area recently. An MP said banditry attacks were instigated by people who want Kapedo to be annexed to Baringo.
Following heavy-handed treatment by police against a MP, residents of Cheptiret protest the action, calling for the local police station to be shut down. Exact date not known - source date is 07/11.
Residents of Homa Bay town and its environs protest against a three-day power blackout.
Residents protest against an MP over a tax law violation.
An outspoken moderate Muslim cleric and al Shabaab critic was assassinated outside his mosque in Mombasa. Perpetrators remain unknown.
Dock workers protest at Mombasa port against inter-political union activities.

A group of youths threw stones at Administration Police officers on night curfew patrol in Lamu. The officers were pelted with stones from a rooftop. No reported injures. The rioters were adverse to the curfew.
Six al Shabaab suspects were shot dead and a soldier seriously injured in an attempted invasion of the KDF Nyali Barracks in Mombasa early in the day.

One person was hacked to death and four others seriously injured in a fresh attack in Bora Moyo village of Kipini. The violence began when a militia from Garjel community attacked the town when they believed its residents had stolen a herd of goats.

At least 24 police officers and Kenya Police Reservists (KPR) are feared dead, 17 injured, in a fresh attack in Kapedo in Tiaty Sub-county Baringo County after Pokot raiders attacked the at Lomelo and Kapau areas of the city.
The Jomo Kenyatta University of Agriculture and Technology (JKUAT) has been closed indefinitely after students went on rampage over a fee.

Seven police members are dead and 17 missing following an attack on their post by local tribesmen. Attackers targeted three police vehicles and burned one of them. The motive for the attack is not known. A similar attack occurred in the area the previous week.
Fighting between two South Sudanese tribes carries over into a second day.
Traders in Lamu protest for a second consecutive day. Police reported involvement.

Nine refugees are known to have been killed and a number of others wounded in days of fighting in the Kakuma refugee camp. The fighting started after an attempted rape of a nine-year-old Nuer girl by a Dinka boy. Though the fighting mainly centered between the two South Sudanese actors, several others from Central Africa were also involved.
Students of Laikipia University in Kitale and Kapenguria protest the college CEOs decision to relocate them to the Eldoret campus.
Students of Laikipia University in Kitale and Kapenguria protest the college CEOs decision to relocate them to the Eldoret campus.

Lamu residents have again taken to the streets to protest the continued extension of the night curfew which has been in force for more than three months now. Police were deployed to disperse the protesters.
A vigilante mob attack and kill a robbery suspect in the Nduuri of Embu.
A vigilante mob lynch a murder suspect in Mukindu village in Ol Kalou.

Mutige Secondary School students walked out in protest against the administrations failure to address their grievances (the students want medical attention for the injured, new toilets, transport and leakage in classrooms and dormitories fixed). The more than 200 students marched to the countys headquarters in Kerugoya.
Residents of the Milano area of Malindi town demonstrated against the buying of land by a business tycoon.
Residents of Majengo town in Vihiga county protest, demanding an audience with the Governor of the region to express their grievance over a recent spate of robberies.
Non-violent activity: A group of Muslim youth forcibly overtake a mosque in Mombasa, and ejected its moderate imam and management committee. Injuries/causalities not known.

University of Eldoret students took to the streets in protest over a directive that they sit special exams. The students claimed that they were not ready for the exams and that they were not given time to prepare.
Twelve people were injured, four of them critically at Bula Sheikh in Garissa town when unknown assailants hurled a grenade at a shop.
Suspected local tribesmen attack a police post in Kapedo. Five dead, including three police officers.

Residents of Maguguni protest along the Mombasa-Nairobi highway for five hours to protest grabbing of the land by CORD corporation leader Raila Odinga. CORD is apparently interested in petroleum prospects on the plot.

Dedan Kimathi University of Technology in Nyeri closed indefinitely following a protest by the students against the alleged incompetence of their Vice Chancellor. The over 500 students shattered window panes in lecture halls; destroyed two university buses, a private vehicle and the students welfare building; set a thicket in the school on fire and harassed motorists along Nyeri-Nyahururu highway. They later engaged armed police officers in running battles before they were dispersed with teargas. A police officer reported an injury. There were additional riots at Karatina University, also in Nyeri.

Mashujaa Day celebrations were disrupted when supporters of a Kirinyaga Central MP (TNA) engaged youths (affiliation unknown) at Kerugoya Stadium. Chaos erupted when the youths stormed the venue of the event and started booing the MP as he addressed residents. Injuries reported.

KDF forces kill five suspected al Shabaab fighters who were attempting to drive an explosive laden car into Kenya from Ethiopia. Mandera is situated at a point where a border is shared by both Ethiopia and Somalia.
Unknown gunmen killed a police officer near the border with Somalia before escaping.
200+ Muslims demonstrated against the 6pm-6am curfew in [Kenya] on Lamu Island. The group asserted the curfew hurts the local fishing economy.
Members of the Olomismis Group Ranch in Trans Mara protested against their officials mismanagement. The exact location of the protest is not known.

A senior Kenyan county official escaped death narrowly after an Improvised Explosive Device (IED) exploded as he was being driven to his office in the border town of Rhamu, Mandera. Perpetrators not known. Two injuries reported.

Drivers in Makutano and Kapenguria towns, West Pokot protested against the poor state of the Makutano-Alale road outside of Makutano. They blocked the road to the governor and county commissioners offices for several hours.

Drivers in Makutano and Kapenguria towns, West Pokot protested against the poor state of the Makutano-Alale road outside of Makutano. They blocked the road to the governor and county commissioners offices for several hours.

Protesters blocked the Nairobi Nakuru highway at Kwambira in Limuru after a 43 year old man was found murdered near his home. The protesters lit bonfires and blocked the road with stones, accusing the government of laxity in providing security.

Turkana Governor Asks Security Council to Help Stop Area Killings
Turkana Governor Asks Security Council to Help Stop Area Killings
Mine workers of the G-5 group of Companies instituted a two-day peaceful strike action from Monday on the compound of the company in Kinjor, Grand Cape Mount County over payment of benefits
Workers of China Union in Bong Mines, Bong County went on a go-slow protest from 1st to 6th May demanding better conditions at work.

A major check point in Kolahun District, Lofa County has been completely vandalized by some motorcyclists in defense of one of their colleagues who was said to have been flogged allegedly by an officer of the Liberia National Police (LNP) in Lofa County.

Seven hundred Liberian Ebola workers took to the streets of the capital Monrovia for a second day on Saturday to demand promised hazard pay. The workers hired by MSF on Saturday blocked the entrance to Liberias biggest Ebola facility.

Enraged motorcyclists resorted to violence in Redlight, Paynesville yesterday in retaliation for the alleged killing of their fellow rider by a police officer. The rioting resulted in the burning down of a police substation. Several police officers reportedly sustained serious injuries and were taken to a nearby health facility.

A Liberian police officer allegedly beat a motorcyclist to death following a heated dispute between the police officer (not named) and a rider only identified as Alfred. Government claims the motorist fell from his bike when he was fleeing from Police after he allegedly assaulted one of them at the GSA Road intersection.

A motorcyclist was killed by a soldier of the Armed Forces of Liberia following a scuffle on Tuesday in Thinker Village Community in Paynesville. Meanwhile, police have arrested the soldier and are investigating the event.

Workers of almost all of Liberias Ebola Treatment Units (ETUs) have staged a major protest in Monrovia, demanding benefits owed them by the Government of Liberia. The workers, predominantly healthcare practitioners, gathered at the seat of the Liberian legislature early Thursday morning to inform lawmakers about their over four months unpaid benefits.

Students of Cestos High School in Rivercess County yesterday morning stormed the county administration building to express their anger and frustration, chanting, ""No renovation, no school, no By-Election."" According to the reports, the students broke doors, windows, chairs and other furniture in the administrative building housing the Superintendents compound. Just before the day ended, the police gained control of the crowd and managed to arrest a student who is believed to be the leader of the demonstration.

Several aggrieved citizens of Giah Town, Disco Hill, Margibi County on Tuesday, April 7 blocked the only road leading to a place where Ebola bodies are buried. The citizens say the Government of Liberia owes them a balance of US$25,000 for the 25 acres of land, which they provided to the government.

A ""corroner jury"" team that went to investigate the death of a disabled man who was beaten by DEA officials was unable to interview people on the crime scene because the area was hostile, and protests were ongoing.
In Mangochi, Muslims protested for a stop to the use of Muslim women as dancers in political rallies. Banda was using women dressed in the hijab and performing the ""Zikiri"" at political rallies.
Key witness for cashgate scandal murdered

Police condemned mob justice at Mawila elementary school where ""where students allegedly assaulted to death a man and set him ablaze for allegedly stealing two pairs of trousers and a pair of shoes from one of the hostels early morning Tuesday. ""
A petrol bomb was thrown into a DPP car.

Opposition DPP supporters rioted Bandas speech In Thyolo. They threw stones at PP supporters and broke several cars. Police intervened by firing teargas and rubber bullets. 1 rioter and 1 police officer died in the chaos.
After the riots, members of the Peoples Party beat up an aid to the oppositions presidential candidate.
Protests for ""call for the disclosure of the names of 68 public officials and business people being tried for corruption in the country""
Protests for ""President Joyce Banda to resign and announced a series of protests and disobedience campaigns. ""
A man attempted to enter the home of his ex wife but when the ex heard someone enter the house, she called for the community. The community rioted/acted as mob justice and killed the man.

Students rioted the school after a teacher banned students from class for not paying for a broken chair. When police arrived, students pelted stones at the police to which the police responded with tear gas.
Two people were burned to death as a result of mob justice.

A joint operation by French and Malian armed forces killed at least 7 militant Islamists of the al-Murabitoun group, and at least 3 were taken prisoner. Among those killed was Ahmed el Tilemsi, the leader of the group.

3 Malian civilians from the same family were kidnapped by armed men near Menaka. They are believed to have been taken by MUJAO, as other attacks have taken place in the same area carried out by MUJAO.
3 Chadian peacekeepers were injured, one seriously, when their vehicle hit a mine near Aguelhoc.

French forces have carried out 5 days of air operations, including airstrikes, over the Amettetai valleys in northern Mali. Four arms caches were destroyed and training camps were targeted. Casualties were not reported.
Two soldiers killed and four or more wounded in a convoy providing security to a government minister when they drove over a landmine.

38 to 100 Chadian MINUSMA soldiers abandoned their base in protest of late payments and demanding better working conditions. They returned after two days when MINUSMA agreed to improve camp conditions.
In Aguelhok and Kidal, suspected al-Qaeda-linked rebels kidnapped 10 children and killed 2 others who tried to escape.
In Aguelhok and Kidal, suspected al-Qaeda-linked rebels kidnapped 10 children and killed 2 others who tried to escape.
Detonation: A suicide bomber blew himself up in a market, causing no casualties or major property damage. No group claimed the attack.
2 Tuaregs who had disappeared earlier in November on the border with Algeria were found dead near Kidal bound in a mat and a blanket. It is not clear who killed them.
2 youths were kidnapped from a convoy traveling from Algeria to Gao. They were taken by armed men near Anefis. Reports disagree about motives for the kidnapping.
2 youths on a motorcycle opened fire on a bar, killing a young man and injuring 6 civilians, 4 seriously. The attackers are believed to have been Islamist militants.

Two dozen ""militants"" were neutralized (killed/captured) in an operation involving forces from France, Mauritania, Niger, Mali and Chad as part of Operation Barkhane. Uncertain number of deaths coded as 10.
3 civilians were wounded when their truck hit a mine.
The Malian military has allegedly besieged the town of Bira near Timbuktu.
2 soldiers were killed and at least 4 other wounded by a roadside explosive device near the town of Almoustrate.

The Malian military has claimed that it was engaged in a clash with the MAA near its base in the Gourma area. It has said that 20 rebels were arrested and 1 fighter killed, while a Tuareg spokesman said 3 rebels and 9 soldiers died. Independent sources say there were a number of deaths on both sides.
